@Collie Pig-Latin is easier thought of as a phonetic trick than a spelling trick. The consonant sound (whatever precedes the vowel) gets removed from the beginning of a word or syllable and shoved at the end, followed by an ‚Äúay‚Äù sound.

Entree follows this pattern: It‚Äôs an ‚Äúon‚Äù sound (as in ‚ÄúEn garde‚Äù) followed by one or more consonants (‚Äútr‚Äù) followed by an ‚Äúay‚Äù sound. on + tr + ay -> tr + on.

The phonetic reasoning is how things like ‚Äúau lait‚Äù (pronounced ‚Äúow lay‚Äù) become ‚Äúlow.‚Äù Or ‚Äúunder way‚Äù‚Äù becomes ‚Äúwonder‚Äù. Or ‚Äúe bay‚Äù becomes ‚Äúbe‚Äù. Or ‚Äúaverage o-jay‚Äù becomes ‚Äúaverage joe.‚Äù
